SIMPLE: express
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Express
<hw>Ex*press"</hw> <pr>(⟦ecr⟧ks*pr⟦ecr⟧s")</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>expr⟦egrave⟧s</ets>, L. <ets>expressus</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>exprimere</ets> to express; <ets>ex</ets>. out + <ets>premere</ets>
To press. See <er>Press</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Exactly
representing; exact.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their human countenance⟦br⟧
The <qex>express</qex> resemblance of the gods.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Directly and distinctly stated; declared in terms;
not implied or left to inference; made unambiguous by intention and
care; clear; not dubious; <as>as, <ex>express</ex> consent; an
<ex>express</ex> statement.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have <xex>express</xex> commandment.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Intended for a particular purpose; relating to an
express; sent on a particular errand; dispatched with special speed;
<as>as, an <ex>express</ex> messenger or train</as>. Also used
adverbially.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> A messenger sent <qex>express</qex> from the other world.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>of or pertaining to an <cref>express train</cref> or
other conveyance designated an express{5}; making few or no intermediate
stops; <as>as, an <ex>express</ex> stop; an <ex>express</ex> fare; an
<ex>express</ex> elevator</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Express color</b></col>. <fld>(Law)</fld> <cd>See the
Note under <er>Color</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 8.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Explicit; clear; unambiguous. See
<er>Explicit</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Express</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Express
<hw>Ex*press"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>expr⟦egrave⟧s</ets>
a messenger.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A clear image or representation; an
expression; a plain declaration.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The only remanent <qex>express</qex> of Christ's sacrifice on
earth.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A messenger sent on a special errand; a courier;
hence, a regular and fast conveyance; commonly, a company or system for
the prompt and safe transportation of merchandise or parcels.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An express office.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She charged him . . . to ask at the <qex>express</qex> if anything
came up from town.</q> <rj><qau>E. E. Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That which is sent by an express messenger or
message.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Eikon Basilike.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>a railway train or bus for transporting passengers
or goods with speed and punctuality; a train or bus that does not stop
at certain stations. Contrasted to <contr>local</contr>; <as>as, take
the <ex>express</ex> to get there faster</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> express train.</syn>
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Express office</b></col>, <cd>an office where packages
for an express are received or delivered.</cd> -- <col><b>Express
train</b></col>, <cd>a railway train (such as a subway train) that does
not stop at certain stations, but only at stations designated
<ecol><b>express stops</b></ecol>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Express</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Express
<hw>Ex*press"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Expressed</conjf><pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Expressing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>espresser</ets>,
<ets>expresser</ets>, L. <ets>exprimere</ets>, <ets>expressum</ets>. See
<er>Express</er>, <pos>a.</pos>; cf. <er>Sprain</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To press or squeeze out; <as>as, to <ex>express</ex> the juice of
grapes, or of apples</as>; hence, to extort; to elicit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the fruits out of which drink is <qex>expressed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And th'idle breath all utterly <qex>expressed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Halters and racks can not <qex>express</qex> from thee⟦br⟧
More than by deeds.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make or offer a representation of; to show by a
copy or likeness; to represent; to resemble.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Each skillful artist shall <qex>express</qex> thy form.</q>
<rj><qau>E. Smith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So kids and whelps their sires and dams <qex>express</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To give a true impression of; to represent and make
known; to manifest plainly; to show in general; to exhibit, as an
opinion or feeling, by a look, gesture, and esp. by language; to
declare; to utter; to tell.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My words <qex>express</qex> my purpose.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>expressed</qex> in their lives those excellent doctrines
of morality.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make known the opinions or feelings of; to
declare what is in the mind of; to show (one's self); to cause to
appear; -- used reflexively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mr. Phillips did <qex>express</qex> with much indignation against
me, one evening.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To denote; to designate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Moses and Aaron took these men, which are <qex>expressed</qex> by
their names.</q> <rj><qau>Num. i. 17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To send by express messenger; to forward by special
opportunity, or through the medium of an express; <as>as, to
<ex>express</ex> a package</as>.</def></p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Genetics)</fld> <def>to produce products that cause
the appearance of the corresponding phenotype; -- of a gene or of an
organism with a specific gene; <as>as, to <ex>express</ex> the
beta-galactosidase gene</as>,</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To declare; utter; signify; testify;
intimate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Expressage</ent>⟦br⟧
